    In the sixth summer of His Majesty's reign, the government and examination bureau were commanded to carefully select fifteen scholars of letters and have them serve concurrently in the Literary Repository. When their studies were complete, they were to gather at the Repository and together engage in mutual discourse and mutual refinement. They were also permitted to freely consult the rare manuscripts and obscure texts housed in the Royal Lectures, to cultivate broad learning. Each month on the tenth and twentieth days, the Minister of Letters and the Chief Lecturer of the Repository would convene to discuss the books being studied, always assigning themes for composition and grading the results to present to the throne. This occurred twice monthly throughout the year, and at year's end their performances were compared, with the excellent promoted and the poor demoted, their stipends and ranks adjusted accordingly.

    When the examination began on the eighth month's day of Renzi, I happened to have another engagement. Together with the Chief Lecturer, I took the test. His Majesty summoned me and spoke thus: "Neither letters nor arms can be neglected. I have always held the scholarly traditions in great esteem, yet recent border duties have prevented me from often joining in learned discourse. Yet not for a moment does this leave my heart. In the matter of reviving the scholarly way, I ask that you and your peers give your utmost. Today I bestow upon you wine and music, that you might convey my sentiments to the other scholars and enjoy yourselves fully."

    The scholars, hearing these commands, could not contain their gratitude. Soon the Right Vice-Minister of State arrived bearing the imperial wine. Thereupon the grand feast was laid out in splendor, the imperial delicacies arranged in abundance. The scholars in turn bowed low and drank the cups bestowed upon them. Celestial music was performed as if the very harmonies of heaven descended upon the purple heavens. The king commanded that each compose a verse of thanks for the wine and music bestowed—an honor beyond measure. Each scholar seized brush and completed their verses on the spot. The drinking games were conducted with strict propriety, none daring to refuse. Soon satiated and intoxicated, they overflowed with joy—some dancing, some stamping their feet, some singing, some chanting softly, some slumping against the walls in drowsy contentment, others rising to recite anew. Their forms and expressions were infinitely varied, yet all were drunk upon the royal grace. Thus they reveled through the night until dawn, when the gathering dispersed. The next morning they approached the palace to express their thanks, presenting the verses they had composed. His Majesty examined them and found them excellent, commanding the court painters to create an image to preserve this occasion for posterity.

    Alas! Truly this was a great moment in the scholarly world.

    I humbly reflect that talented persons are the instruments through which a nation is governed. Letters provide the warp and arms the weft, differing in form yet unified in function—like the wheels of a carriage or the wings of a bird, wherein lies no essential distinction of weight or lightness. In the tensions and releases, the visible and hidden workings of statecraft, how can a ruler lean toward one side? Yet the foundation and sequence of these matters must surely be understood. Moral learning provides the root of governance; literary arts are the means by which the world is ordered. Ritual and music, education and transformation—all manifest letters. State affairs and proclamations—all manifest the Way. This is what we treasure in the work of true scholars, not merely the study of texts or the pursuit of ornamental style.

    Though the flourishing of letters relates to the patterns of heaven and earth, the impulse to cultivate and perfect them has always depended upon the guidance of rulers and teachers. Should a ruler genuinely cherish and patiently nurture these, with encouragement and reward properly applied, what harvest might we not reap in days to come?

    Our Sovereign, Heaven-favored with sagacity and commanded by the divine mandate, has achieved great military glory while illuminating civilian culture. He wields the threads of heaven and earth, opens and closes the past and present, and yet still broadly welcomes scholars and strengthens the foundations of the realm. The grace of the Aria plant falls deep, the teaching of the jujube and oak spreads complete. In quiet chambers he grants occasions for discourse, allowing his scholars wide hearing and distant vision, bestowing favor upon them daily. His effort to inspire this age and mold myriad things into noble form can truly be called magnificent. In the art of nurturing and perfecting talents, he takes every care, establishing examinations to further stimulate the worthy, so that they may sharpen their keen intelligence and polish their rhetorical powers, soaring through the fields of skill and galloping through the gardens of texts—knowing daily what was unknown before, never forgetting each month what has been learned. Their aspirations grow richer, their mastery more refined. Thus shall there emerge in great numbers not merely those who climb the halls of Zhu Xi and Cheng Yi or follow in the footsteps of Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan, but those who uphold the nation's fabric and illuminate its sacred transformation.

    Such are his far-reaching plans and weighty hopes. How can scholars not be moved to vigorous action?

    Turning to antiquity, the sage-king Wen of Zhou produced men of talent, and the Ming Emperor of Han honored the scholarly way—nearly paralleling these times. Yet in the methods of encouragement and the generosity of favor, there is even more. When the Tang's Taizong established his dynasty, he also established an academy, welcoming literary talents from all directions. Fang Xuanling, Du Ruhui, Yu Shinan, and Chu Suiliang—all served as resident scholars, rotating their duties. Imperial treasures were shared with them, and in the intervals of official business they debated the classics, sometimes continuing through the night without rest. He commanded the painter Yan Liben to capture their likenesses, which later generations have treasured as a beautiful tale. Our time bears resemblance to this, yet whether the teaching of benevolence and righteousness was so diligently practiced then, or whether the honoring of letters and cultivation of the scholarly way sprang from genuine sincerity as in our sage king, remains a question. Should it have been mere outward show, compelled and artificial, then it would deserve only the painter's mockery and merit no admiration.

    I, despite my meager talents, have received undeserved favor and esteem, becoming steward of literary affairs and the recipient of personal royal grace. Such honors are incomparable. I cannot remain silent but must offer some words celebrating His Majesty's reverence for the Way and his honor toward scholars. Thus I set down this complete account for the knowledge of future ages without end.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Literary Repository' (Yeomungwan) was an institution established to gather and cultivate literary talent in the Joseon court.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Aria plant' and 'jujube and oak' are classical references to the gentle nurturing and education of the people, drawn from Confucian texts.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhu Xi and Cheng Yi were Song Dynasty Neo-Confucian philosophers; Han Yu and Liu Zongyuan were renowned Tang Dynasty scholar-officials and writers—representing the highest ideals of scholarly and literary achievement.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Yan Liben and the Tang court painters reflects the practice of immortalizing important state occasions through portraiture, considered a mark of historical significance.
